  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Programs\n- Implementing anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Training staff on detection and prevention\n- Establishing internal monitoring systems\n\n4. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Collecting detailed customer information\n- Assessing risk levels of clients\n- Ongoing customer verification\n\n5. International Compliance\n- Following global AML standards\n- Cooperating with international investigations\n- Adhering to regulations like Bank Secrecy Act\n\n6. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers/transactions\n- Developing risk mitigation strategies\n- Conducting periodic risk evaluations\n\n7. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the global financial system's integrity.",
